snippet.textDisplay:
I think it's more along the lines that she has always taken it very personally when the media, other celebrities, and people in general say anything negative about her.She has written songs just like this before, but now she has decided or been told that she should use her fame to promote certain political beliefs. Probably because so many other celebrities have done so following the 2016 presidential election in the USA.

MEAN was about her saying that all her haters were being unreasonable.
SHAKE IT OFF was about her being unaffected by what they said.
BLANK SPACE was her pretending to be in her own words: "...the character I felt the media had written for me, and for a long time I felt hurt by it."
YOU NEED TO CALM DOWN Is largely about anti-LGBT activists, and the idea that they should mind their own business. But the opening lines are not about homophobes, but Swift haters.
THE MAN is about her getting unfairly criticized. She suggests that she wouldn't get hate for the same behaviors if she were a man. She is using sexism as the latest scapegoat for why some people don't like her.

I think most of them just have a different taste in music or are jealous. If Swift could come to terms with the fact that some people will never like her, she'd probably be a lot happier.
